# 🎛️ Trimpot-Controlled OLED Menu System using STM32

## 📌 Overview

This project implements a **menu-driven embedded interface** using a trimpot (analog input) and an OLED display. The trimpot is used to navigate between different modes, and the selected mode is displayed on the OLED with a cursor indicator.

This system demonstrates analog-based user interaction without buttons, providing smooth and intuitive control.

---

## 🎯 Features

* Analog input-based menu navigation
* OLED display interface (I2C)
* Real-time mode selection
* Flicker-free UI (updates only on change)
* Simple embedded UI design

---

## 🧠 Working Principle

The trimpot provides a variable analog voltage that is read using the ADC of the STM32. The ADC value is divided into ranges, each corresponding to a specific menu option:

* Low range → Mode 1
* Mid range → Mode 2
* High range → Mode 3

The selected mode is highlighted on the OLED using a cursor (`>`), and the display updates only when the selection changes.

---

## 🔧 Hardware Used

* STM32 (e.g., STM32F446RE / Nucleo board)
* Trimpot (Potentiometer)
* SSD1306 OLED Display (I2C)

---

## 🔌 Pin Configuration

| Peripheral    | Pin |
| ------------- | --- |
| Trimpot (ADC) | PA0 |
| I2C SCL       | PB8 |
| I2C SDA       | PB9 |

---

## ⚙️ Software Configuration

* IDE: STM32CubeIDE
* Language: C (HAL Drivers)
* ADC Resolution: 12-bit
* I2C Speed: 100 kHz

---

## 📺 OLED Display

Example UI:

```id="m1a9xq"
>MODE1
 MODE2
 MODE3
```

* `>` indicates selected mode
* Display updates only when selection changes

---

## 🔄 System Logic

```id="5gnc7y"
Read ADC → Map to range → Select mode → Update OLED
```

---

## 📊 ADC Mapping

```id="q4c2zo"
0     - 1365  → MODE1
1365  - 2730  → MODE2
2730  - 4095  → MODE3
```

---

## ▶️ How to Run

1. Open project in STM32CubeIDE
2. Build and flash the code
3. Rotate trimpot
4. Observe menu selection change on OLED

---

## ⚠️ Notes

* Ensure stable power for trimpot
* ADC values may slightly vary → adjust thresholds if needed
* OLED I2C address typically `0x3C`

---

